Development Model:

Open Source: Mozilla Firefox is an open-source web browser, which means that its source code is freely available for anyone to view, modify, and contribute to. This open development model allows developers from around the world to collaborate on improving the browser.
Licensing:

Mozilla Firefox is released under the Mozilla Public License (MPL), which is an open-source software license. The MPL is a permissive license that allows for the free use, modification, and distribution of the software, provided that any changes to the code are also made available under the same license.
Mode of Funding:

Mozilla Corporation, a subsidiary of the Mozilla Foundation, generates revenue primarily through search partnerships. Firefox includes a default search engine, and Mozilla earns a portion of the revenue generated from user searches conducted through Firefox. They also receive donations from individuals and organizations.
Commercial and Non-Commercial Use:

Mozilla Firefox is available for both commercial and non-commercial use. Individuals, businesses, and organizations can use Firefox for free. The open-source nature of Firefox allows customization and deployment in various settings, including commercial enterprises and non-profit organizations.
Overall, Mozilla Firefox's open-source development model, permissive licensing, revenue from search partnerships, and availability for both commercial and non-commercial use contribute to its widespread adoption and continued development as a popular web browser.




